# Coding standards – PandaTrack

## Language: English only (except i18n)

**All code output must be in English.** This includes:

- Variable names, function names, type/interface names, and identifiers
- Comments and documentation (JSDoc, README, inline comments)
- Commit messages, log messages, and error messages in code
- Test descriptions and assertion messages
- API response messages or developer-facing strings in source code

**Exception:** Anything that depends on the active locale (user-facing text, asset paths, or other locale-specific configuration) must live in the locale files under `src/i18n/locales/` (e.g. `en/`, `es/`). Do not hardcode copy or locale-specific values in components. The keys and the content of those files may be in any language the product supports; only the **code** (identifiers, comments, commit messages, etc.) is required to be in English.

## Fundamental principles

- **Clarity over cleverness**: Write code that is easy to understand. Prioritize readability over micro-optimizations.
- **Consistency**: Use the same patterns across the entire codebase.
- **Single responsibility**: Each function, component, and module should do one thing well.
- **Explicit over implicit**: Avoid magic values and hidden side effects. Prefer explicit configuration, types, and dependencies.
- **Spelling and grammar**: Use correct spelling and grammar in all of the above (English).
- **No em dash**: Never use the em dash character (—) when generating text. Use a hyphen (-), a colon (:), or rephrase the sentence instead.

## No planning references in code comments

Do not include planning metadata in source code comments or JSDoc, including:

- Feature IDs like `FEAT-XXXX`
- Terms like `epic`, `slice`, `ticket`, or issue numbers/URLs
- References to implementation phases tied to planning artifacts

Code comments must explain behavior and intent only, independent of project management tracking.

## Reuse existing components and elements

Prefer reusing existing building blocks so the app stays consistent and maintainable.

- **Core and module components first**: Before adding raw HTML or new components, check `src/components/core/` and `src/components/modules/`. Use `Typography` for paragraph or span text, `Heading` for headings, `Button` for actions, etc., so styling and behavior stay consistent.
- **Semantic HTML when no component fits**: If no core or module component matches the need, use the appropriate HTML element (`<p>`, `<button>`, `<nav>`, etc.) with the project’s Tailwind/semantic tokens. Do not create a one-off component when a simple element plus `className` is enough.
- **Do not force reuse when purpose or design differs**: Reuse only when the use case and visual intent align. For example, use `Button` for primary/secondary CTAs, but a plain `<button>` or `<div>` with `role="button"` for a backdrop overlay that closes a drawer, or for custom controls that do not look or behave like app buttons.

```tsx
// ✅ Prefer: core component for body text
<Typography size="sm" className="text-text-muted mt-3 text-center">
  {t("image.disclaimer")}
</Typography>

// ❌ Avoid: raw <p> when Typography exists and fits
<p className="text-text-muted mt-3 text-center text-xs">{t("image.disclaimer")}</p>
```

```tsx
// ✅ Fine: plain element when purpose is different from core Button (e.g. overlay, custom control)
<button type="button" aria-label="Close menu" className="inset-0 ..." onClick={onClose} />

// ✅ Fine: use Button for CTAs that match its variants
<Button variant="primary">Join the waitlist</Button>
```

## Apply DRY: extract repeated code into reusable pieces

Whenever the same components, functions, behavior, or logic appears in more than one place, extract it into a reusable unit instead of duplicating. Apply DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself) by default.

- **Repeated UI, layout, or form structure**: Extract a shared component. Prefer reusing existing components from `src/components/core/` or `src/components/modules/` first; if the repeated block has no suitable component, create one (in core, modules, or route-level `_components` as per project structure). Pass varying parts as props or children.
- **Repeated logic or calculations**: Extract to a shared function. Place it in `src/lib/` for app-wide use, in `src/hooks/` for reactive logic, or in route-level `_utils`/`_actions` when scoped to a segment.
- **Repeated behavior or flow** (e.g. same submit flow with different endpoints, same validation pattern): Extract to a shared function, hook, or small module so one place owns the behavior and callers stay thin.

**Exception:** Do not extract when it would hurt readability or create unnecessary abstraction. If the "reusable" version would be full of conditionals, obscure the intent, or only be used twice with very different futures, prefer a bit of duplication. Clarity and ease of understanding trump DRY when they conflict.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: same layout and form structure duplicated in two pages
// SignInForm.tsx and SignUpForm.tsx each with 60+ lines of identical shell + similar fields

// ✅ Prefer: shared layout and shared form component; each page keeps only its specific logic
<AuthFormLayout title={...} footerLinkHref={...}>
  <EmailPasswordForm idPrefix="signin" ... onSubmit={handleSignIn} />
</AuthFormLayout>
```

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid: same validation or format logic copy-pasted in several components
if (!email.trim() || !password.trim()) setError(t("invalidCredentials"));
// ... repeated elsewhere

// ✅ Prefer: one helper or hook, reused everywhere
const { validate, error } = useEmailPasswordValidation({ t });
```

## Reusable constants for app-wide values

Whenever a value is reused across the app (routes, event names, app name, shared config, etc.), define it as a constant and reference it everywhere instead of repeating literals.

- **Group in an object** when you have several related values: `ROUTES`, `POSTHOG_EVENTS`, `CONTACT_INFO`, `COOKIES`. Use a **single exported constant** when the value stands alone: `APP_NAME`, `THEME_STORAGE_KEY`.
- Keep these constants in a central place (e.g. `src/lib/constants.ts`) so they stay easy to find and update.

```typescript
// ✅ Prefer: reuse from constants
import { ROUTES } from "@/lib/constants";
<Link href={`/${locale}${ROUTES.terms}`} />

// ❌ Avoid: repeating the same path or string in multiple files
<Link href={`/${locale}/terms`} />
```

## Analytics (PostHog) for clickable and meaningful interactions

Whenever you add or change **buttons**, **links**, **clickable elements**, or any UI that represents a meaningful user action (CTAs, share actions, nav, form submit, toggles), apply the analytics rules so those interactions can be tracked.

- **Follow the PostHog rule**: See `.cursor/rules/posthog-events.mdc` for when to add events, how to name them in `POSTHOG_EVENTS`, and how to attach them (e.g. `data-ph-event`, `posthogEvent` / `posthogProps` on `Button`).
- **Do not skip tracking** on new interactive UI: if the element is clickable or triggers a conversion-related action, add the corresponding PostHog event as part of the same change.

## Repeated components: use array + map when it stays simple

When a series of components repeat with only value changes (same structure, different props or copy), define the values in an array and render with `.map()` instead of writing each instance by hand. This keeps the UI easy to extend and avoids copy-paste errors.

- **Define an array** (or build it from state/props) where each item holds the varying values.
- **Use a stable `key`** when mapping (e.g. a unique id or a field that identifies the item).
- If some items are conditional, you can build the array conditionally (e.g. spread `...(condition ? [item] : [])`) or filter before mapping.

**Exception: prefer repeating the component when the array would hurt readability.** If the array needs a lot of conditionals, inline JSX in items, or per-item logic so that the data structure is harder to follow than the UI, repeat the component in JSX instead. Clarity and ease of understanding trump DRY here.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: repeating the same component structure manually when the list is simple data
<a href={whatsappHref} ...><SimpleIconSvg path={siWhatsapp.path} /><span>{t("whatsapp")}</span></a>
<a href={xHref} ...>...</a>
<a href={facebookHref} ...>...</a>

// ✅ Prefer: array of values + map when items are uniform
const shareLinkItems = [ { href: whatsappHref, iconPath: siWhatsapp.path, labelKey: "whatsapp" }, ... ];
{shareLinkItems.map((item) => (
  <a key={item.labelKey} href={item.href} ...>
    <SimpleIconSvg path={item.iconPath} />
    <span>{t(item.labelKey)}</span>
  </a>
))}
```

```tsx
// ✅ Prefer: repeat the component when the "array" would be full of conditionals and logic
{hasNativeShare && (
  <Button onClick={handleNativeShare} ...>
    <Share2 ... />
    <span>{t("shareButton")}</span>
  </Button>
)}
<Button onClick={handleCopyLink} aria-live="polite" aria-atomic ...>
  <Link2 ... />
  <span>{copiedFeedbackShown ? <span className="text-success">{t("copiedFeedback")}</span> : t("copyLinkButton")}</span>
</Button>

// ❌ Avoid: forcing an array that needs conditional spread, inline JSX in items, and extra types
const shareButtonItems = [ ...(hasNativeShare ? [{ ... }] : []), { label: copiedFeedbackShown ? <span>...</span> : t("copyLinkButton"), ... } ];
{shareButtonItems.map((item) => <Button ...>{item.icon}<span>{item.label}</span></Button>)}
```

## Multi-state or multi-view components: extract complex states

When a component has several distinct states or views (e.g. loading vs content, form vs success, empty vs list), and any of those states is **complex** (non-trivial business logic, many lines of JSX, validation, or multiple sub-sections), put each complex state or view in its **own component**. The parent keeps the state and conditionally renders the right child. This improves readability and makes each piece easier to reason about and test.

- **Keep the parent thin**: it should mainly handle which state is active and pass props/callbacks to the view components.
- **Extract when it’s complex**: a few lines or a simple message can stay inline; a long form, a full success/error UI, or logic-heavy blocks should be their own component.
- **Name by state or role**: e.g. `WaitlistForm`, `WaitlistShare`, `OrderSummary`, `EmptyState`.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: one big component with long inline branches
function Waitlist() {
  const [state, ...] = useActionState(...);
  const showSuccess = state?.success === true;
  return (
    <section>
      {showSuccess ? (
        <div className="...">
          <Typography>...</Typography>
          <div className="...">
            {/* many share buttons and logic */}
          </div>
        </div>
      ) : (
        <form className="mt-10 space-y-5">
          {/* many fields, labels, validation, submit button */}
        </form>
      )}
    </section>
  );
}

// ✅ Prefer: parent chooses state; each view is its own component
function Waitlist() {
  const [state, ...] = useActionState(...);
  const showSuccess = state?.success === true;
  return (
    <section>
      {showSuccess ? (
        <WaitlistShare locale={locale} />
      ) : (
        <WaitlistForm ... />
      )}
    </section>
  );
}
```

## No magic numbers or values

Do not use raw numbers or strings except in trivial cases (0, 1). Use named constants or variables that provide context.

**Exception:** This does not apply when the value is passed to a prop whose name already conveys the meaning. No need for an extra constant if the prop name makes the value self-explanatory (e.g. `viewBox="0 0 24 24"`, `width={24}`, `size={18}`).

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
if (user.age > 18) { ... }

// ✅ Do this
const LEGAL_ADULT_AGE = 18;
if (user.age > LEGAL_ADULT_AGE) { ... }
```

```typescript
// ✅ Fine: prop name gives context; no constant needed
<svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" width={18} height={18} />

// ❌ Unnecessary: constant adds no clarity over the prop name
const VIEWBOX = "0 0 24 24";
<svg viewBox={VIEWBOX} />
```

## No function drilling

Do not chain function calls directly. Use intermediate variables for readability and debugging.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid
navigator.clipboard.writeText(filterWildcardsForCopy(answer));

// ✅ Do this
const filteredCopyText = filterWildcardsForCopy(answer);
navigator.clipboard.writeText(filteredCopyText);
```

## No inline logic in JSX event handlers

JSX event props (HTML elements and React components) must not contain inline logic. Keep event props as a single function reference or a one-liner that only calls a single function. Any multi-step behavior must live in a named handler function (usually `handle*`).

This makes the UI easy to scan and understand at a glance.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: multiple actions inside the JSX prop
<button
  onClick={() => {
    posthog.capture(POSTHOG_EVENTS.LANDING.MOBILE_MENU_NAV_CLICKED, {
      destination: "waitlist",
      cta_type: "primary",
    });
    onClose();
  }}
/>

// ✅ Prefer: named handler contains the logic
const handleWaitlistClick = () => {
  posthog.capture(POSTHOG_EVENTS.LANDING.MOBILE_MENU_NAV_CLICKED, {
    destination: "waitlist",
    cta_type: "primary",
  });
  onClose();
};

<button onClick={handleWaitlistClick} />
```

```tsx
// ✅ Allowed: direct reference (best when no args needed)
<button onClick={handleSubmit} />

// ✅ Allowed: one-liner that calls a single function (for passing args)
<button onClick={() => handleNavClick("waitlist")} />

// ❌ Avoid: more than one action, even if short
<button onClick={() => (trackClick(), onClose())} />
```

## Naming conventions

| Element | Convention | Example |
|--------|------------|---------|
| Files and directories | camelCase | `userProfile.tsx`, `orderService.ts` |
| Variables and functions | camelCase | `userName`, `fetchOrders()` |
| Types, interfaces, classes | PascalCase | `UserProfile`, `OrderRepository` |
| Constants | UPPER_SNAKE_CASE | `MAX_RETRY_COUNT` |
| React components | PascalCase | `UserCard`, `DashboardLayout` |

Variable names must be self-explanatory and include enough context:

```typescript
// ❌ Bad
const x = 10;

// ✅ Good
const maxLoginAttempts = 10;
```

Group related constants in objects (e.g. in `src/lib/constants.ts`):

```typescript
export const COOKIES = {
  profileId: "profileId",
} as const;
```

## Git branch naming

Format: `[ticket-id]-[clear-description]`. For multi-part work use `-part1`, `-part2`, etc.

Examples: `PT-1-implement-landing`, `PT-2-add-auth-part1`.
